young people have a weak grasp of the principles that underlie our constitutional system. Crucial questions must be answered: How serious is the situation? What role do schools play in shaping civic behavior? Are current education reform initiatives-such as multiculturalism and school choice-counterproductive? How can schools contribute toward reversing the trend?This volume brings together leading thinkers from a variety of disciplines to probe the relation between a healthy democracy and education. Their original and provocative discussions cut across a range of important topics: the cultivation of democratic values, the formation of social capital in schools and communities, political conflict in a pluralist society, the place of religion in public life, the enduring problems of racial inequality. Gathering together the most current research and thinking on education and civil society, this is a book that deserves the attention of everyone who cares about the quality and future of American democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCitizenshipxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aCivicsxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aEducationxAims and objectiveszUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aDamon, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElshtain, Jean Bethke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlazer, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlenn, Charles L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHillygus, D. Sunshine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmes, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel